00:19.340 --> 00:21.060
And here are your hosts.

00:25.480 --> 00:35.120
This is Bill Vernon. And David Crews. George R.R. Martin is one of a group of new
writers born in the post-war baby boom who is becoming a powerful force in the

00:35.120 --> 00:44.320
field of science fiction. We asked Martin his definition of science fiction.
Science fiction isn't about science. It's about old literature. It's about

00:44.320 --> 00:56.700
people and moral issues and the way people relate to each other and good and bad
and love and death and pain and sorrow and all of that stuff. The only thing

00:56.700 --> 01:05.120
that's different about it is he uses a different set of symbols. It tries to get
us out of our here and now world just as traditional fantasy has done for

01:05.120 --> 01:15.900
centuries. But instead of using fantasy type symbols, it uses symbols drawn from
what essentially is the new religion of our modern age, science and technology.

01:17.100 --> 01:27.600
The theme that pervades much of Martin's early work is the intrusion of cold,
hard reality into romance. Martin comments on this element.

01:27.600 --> 01:36.020
The dreams that I grew up with, that other writers of my
generation grew up with. Howard Waldrop, John Varley, people like that have

01:36.020 --> 01:50.360
spoken about it in their own writings. And then the reality unfolded. Our dreams
came true. But they didn't. It wasn't the same dreams. It changed. And in most

01:50.360 --> 02:01.760
cases, it changed for the worse. For the worse. I used, there was a story of
mine called Patrick Henry, Jupiter and the Little Red Brick Spaceship that's

02:01.760 --> 02:13.580
included in Songs of Stars and Shadows. Probably not one of my most famous
stories or one of my better stories. But it's one in which this particular

02:13.580 --> 02:22.820
question is addressed in a very direct kind of manner. Because I use a
protagonist who feels the same way. The World Science Fiction Convention, when

02:22.820 --> 02:33.100
Apollo 11 landed on the moon, gave them a special award for best moon landing
ever. Which I think is completely untrue. In science fiction, there are lots of

02:33.100 --> 02:43.740
moon landings that are much more exciting than the one that Apollo 11 did. In
fact, that's a whole point. I support the space program. I dream of, I think,

02:44.500 --> 02:54.080
it's a route that mankind should go to. And in some ways, it's very tragic
what's happened to it. And what's happened to it is that NASA really messed it

02:54.080 --> 03:02.060
up. They took the greatest adventure in human history and through a supreme
superhuman effort, have managed to make it boring. And that's what's happened to

03:02.060 --> 03:11.600
the American space program. And that's what I tried to address in that
particular story. But the theme in other contexts runs through a lot of my work,

03:11.740 --> 03:22.880
particularly my early work. The fact that we need dreams to sustain us. And that
the dreams are often, I mean, that's part of what morning comes miss fall too.

03:23.020 --> 03:32.540
The dreams are better than the reality. Truth and beauty. Beauty is truth.
Truth, beauty. That is all you know and all you need to know. But it's not true.

03:32.840 --> 03:44.100
Some things are beautiful, but not true. And some things are true, but not
beautiful. I grew up in Bayonne, New Jersey. Little industrial city right

03:44.100 --> 03:51.200
outside of New York. At the time, it was one of the major oil refining centers
in the world. It was true, but it wasn't very beautiful.

03:53.980 --> 04:06.080
And I read books that took place on, you know, Mars and the asteroid belt and
planets of other stars. And they were pretty beautiful in their way, but they

04:06.080 --> 04:10.600
weren't true. So things

04:10.600 --> 04:20.580
don't work out that conveniently. And that's the whole reality romance thing
that much of my work does concern itself with. In an early Martin story,

04:20.760 --> 04:29.100
Slideshow, the space effort is maintained through contributions garnered at
fundraisers. But I wanted to express the fact that I did have reservations and

04:29.100 --> 04:40.120
humanitarian concerns and all that about Earth. But I still think the weight of
that story is very much towards the space thing. And how pitiful it has become

04:40.120 --> 04:50.540
where they have to go around and give slideshows to rich people and hope to get
a little contribution to continue it. But I do see us going that way. More on

04:50.540 --> 04:52.180
George Martin in our next show.

