12:13.820 --> 12:15.520
And here are your hosts.

12:19.840 --> 12:28.900
This is Bill Vernon. And David Crews. Science fiction writer George Martin is the
subject of our show today. Martin spent almost a decade writing short stories

12:28.900 --> 12:36.840
before he published his first novel. Here he comments on the importance of the
short story to the beginning writer. I think that's just the way you break into

12:36.840 --> 12:44.680
the field. And that's one of the strengths of science fiction, is that it's one
of the few branches of literature that still has a viable short story market,

12:45.500 --> 12:56.300
where young writers and beginning writers can learn the ropes, can get their
initial publication. Novels, on the other hand, are not the best way to begin,

12:56.540 --> 13:08.780
as Martin tells us. Novels are large. Novels are formidable pieces of work. You
just don't knock them off in a week or so. And you really have to know what

13:08.780 --> 13:09.240
you're doing.

13:12.300 --> 13:24.400
I wrote a lot of short stories in my early years. Some of them are good, I like
to think. Some of them are maybe even excellent. And some of them are terrible.

13:29.700 --> 13:39.760
And I learned a lot through the process of doing that, and also through the
process of selling them. If I had been writing novels, I mean, it would be very

13:39.760 --> 13:46.720
easy to wash out writing novels. You spend a year and a half writing a book, and
then no one wants to buy it. It's terrible. Or it falls apart at the end. Part

13:46.720 --> 13:56.820
of it's good, part of it's bad. That's a bad way to begin, I think. I've always
felt that it's much better, especially in a field like science fiction, where

13:56.820 --> 14:05.960
you can publish your short stories for any kind of young writer to begin with
short stories, to learn his craft there, also to establish a name for himself by

14:05.960 --> 14:14.700
selling to the market. It's a much sounder commercial strategy. Martin believes
that if one does not establish himself as a short story writer first, it's more

14:14.700 --> 14:25.820
difficult to break into print. You see in the modern, present commercial
marketplace of literature, you see a whole lot of books coming out, first

14:25.820 --> 14:37.540
novels. There's nothing that's more deadly than a first novel. That was not
always the case

14:37.540 --> 14:45.060
in science fiction. Once upon a time, there was a large enough audience that
bought every science fiction book that came out that a writer publishing his

14:45.060 --> 14:54.740
first novel could be short a certain minimum thing. Science fiction's gotten too
big for that now. That's no longer the case. So, a lot of people, Joe Blow

14:54.740 --> 15:05.000
writes his first novel, sells it because it's pretty good, he gets published, he
just dies a dismal, dreary death, because no one's ever heard of him. So, unless

15:05.000 --> 15:13.060
he has some gimmick, unless there's some reason, nobody reads his novel, nobody
gives him a chance. The way I did it, in hindsight, is much the better way. I

15:13.060 --> 15:23.080
built up a reputation over five or six years for my short stories. And when I
finally did write Dying of the Light, my first novel, it was not by Joe Blow. It

15:23.080 --> 15:34.660
was the first novel by George R.R. Martin, ta-da, trumpets, drumroll, and the
world was much more receptive to it than had I thrown it out beforehand. So, I

15:34.660 --> 15:44.380
think any writer wanting to break into science fiction should begin with short
stories and should make a reputation with those and then make the transition to

15:44.380 --> 15:54.820
novels. At the end of each story in Martin's collections is a date and a
location. We asked Martin why he ends his stories in this manner. Instead of

15:54.820 --> 16:04.020
writing the end, you put where you were and what time the story was written. And
it helps put them in a chronological perspective for readers who are interested

16:04.020 --> 16:12.580
in kind of observing the writer's growth because the order that they're
published in is often not at all an appropriate indication of the order that

16:12.580 --> 16:20.020
they were written in, publishing schedules being what they are. Some stories are
rushed into print. Some are held for years. Some stories you can't sell for

16:20.020 --> 16:24.260
years. And you finally find a place for them and they come out five years after
you wrote them.

16:27.280 --> 16:37.560
So, to really get an idea of what kind of evolution changes a writer goes
through, those sorts of dates are important. In our next show, we'll discuss

16:37.560 --> 16:39.360
Martin's novel, Dying of the Light.

