18:09.640 --> 18:11.360
And here are your hosts.

18:16.280 --> 18:25.180
This is David Crews. And Bill Vernon. In today's show, we continue our discussion
with science fiction writer George Martin. Martin's first novel was the

18:25.180 --> 18:34.420
enthusiastically received, critically acclaimed Dying of the Light. The story
behind the title of this novel is interesting. I wrote the book as After the

18:34.420 --> 18:50.080
Festival, which was my title for it. I sold the book to Pocket Books. At the
same time, I sold the version to Analog for serialization in Analog Magazine.

18:51.060 --> 19:05.360
And they wanted it cut considerably. So I cut it for them by 30,000 words, which
is a pretty substantial cut. And when I did that, I said, well, I want this

19:05.360 --> 19:14.240
serial version published under a different title. Because I don't want people
reading a serial and thinking they've read the book. Not when there are 30,000

19:14.240 --> 19:26.300
words difference. The book is a lot better than the serial. So I told the editor
of Analog to call the serial version Mock Man. Because my book was going to be

19:26.300 --> 19:37.860
called After the Festival, which I had written it under. He didn't like the
title Mock Man, but he kind of agreed under protest. Then, my book publisher

19:37.860 --> 19:47.840
calls back and says that the higher up, Peter Mayer, who was running the company
at the time, big publishing hotshot, not a science fiction editor, but the head

19:47.840 --> 19:59.540
of the whole Pocket Books empire then, he didn't like After the Festival as a
title. Because it wasn't science fictional enough. They were willing to make it

19:59.540 --> 20:10.920
after the Star Festival, but that gave me goosebumps and made me want to
decapitate someone. So I said, no, no. But they threw out after the festival. So

20:10.920 --> 20:21.340
I had to come up with a new title. I came up with about 12 of them, most of
which were pretty limp. And I sent in the list of these 12, kind of dreading

20:21.340 --> 20:30.740
which one they would pick, because I didn't like any of them. And then, like two
days after I sent in the list, I thought of Dying in a Light. And I liked that

20:30.740 --> 20:42.120
title a great deal. I liked it almost as much as After the Festival. It's real
close. Right now, I wouldn't know which title I liked best. They're both very

20:42.120 --> 20:52.800
appropriate for the book. And the publisher liked Dying in a Light. I sent it in
two days after the list of 12 bad suggestions. And the publisher said, oh, Dying

20:52.800 --> 21:01.220
in a Light. That's fine. We'll call it that. At that point, I called up the
editor of Analog and said, well, I still want a different title. But After the

21:01.220 --> 21:11.920
Festival is now free because the publisher changed it. So call the serial
version After the Festival. So my original title was used on the serial version,

21:12.100 --> 21:22.000
and the Dying of the Light title from Thomas was used on the book, the fuller
version. One of the themes Martin explores in Dying of the Light is that of the

21:22.000 --> 21:35.860
misunderstanding that can develop between people from different cultures. It's a
very significant point of the book is the role of names, which I call it in the

21:35.860 --> 21:45.180
book, the importance of names, really the importance of language and
linguistics, to what we are able to think, to what we are able to conceive. The

21:45.180 --> 21:55.040
hero of Dying of the Light, the protagonist, gets in trouble throughout the book
because he insists on making false translations. He'll see something and he'll

21:55.040 --> 22:04.340
say, well, these people are slaves. But they're not slaves. They're, you know,
there's a word for it in the book, an alien word, and it's different. There are

22:04.340 --> 22:14.800
important differences from slavery. But he sees it only in his own terms. He
sees people and he has to define them as friends, let us say. When the word is

22:14.800 --> 22:23.760
tain, it means something very different, similar in some ways, different in
other ways. And to really understand another culture, you have to be able to

22:23.760 --> 22:37.380
think in their language, in their terms, and not make false translations to your
own terms that simplify and distort simply by the act of translating. More on

22:37.380 --> 22:38.900
George Martin in our next show.

